/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-callbacks.spec.md:783:- [How Rhei Is Used](rhei-usage.spec.md) - Roles, coordination patterns, and agent workflows
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:3:This document describes how Rhei plans are consumed by agents, humans, and programs. It covers the distinct roles that interact with a plan, the coordination patterns they follow, and how the state machine governs the workflow.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:9:A Rhei plan is a shared artifact read and written by several distinct roles. Each role has a narrow mandate — what it may read, what it may change, and when it must stop.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:26:The plan worker picks up an existing plan and makes progress on it. It is driven entirely by the plan: the state machine defines what transitions are legal, `**Prior:**` edges define what is ready, and state instructions define what to do.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:31:- In interactive/manual execution, advance the state when exit conditions are met (e.g., `draft` → `pending`, `pending` → `agent-review`) or finish directly with `rhei complete` when review is not required.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:32:- In `rhei run` execution, leave state mutation to the orchestrator: the worker produces the required artifacts and exits, and `rhei run` performs the transition.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:35:The plan worker does **not** add tasks, reorder tasks, change dependencies, or delete sections. In interactive/manual execution it may edit `**State:**` values and progress logs inside a task body (including child task bodies). Under `rhei run`, spawned workers leave `**State:**` changes to the orchestrator and only produce the work and artifacts for the current state.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:37:The Plan Worker role corresponds to `worker` [Completion Authority](rhei-agents.spec.md#completion-authority); `rhei run` corresponds to `orchestrator` authority. The same state definition is legal under both — what differs is who decides the state's work is done and drives the resulting transition.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:43:- **Agent reviewer** (`agent-review`): An automated pass that checks the implementation against the task description, its child task nodes, and repository conventions (lint, format, tests). It records concrete findings in the task body or in a required findings artifact when the active state machine declares one. The next transition is then chosen by the active execution model: manually by an interactive worker, or by `rhei run` after the reviewer subprocess exits.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:45:- **Human reviewer** (`human-review`): A human inspects the work. No agent may transition out of this state autonomously. The human decides: return to `pending` (rework), `completed` (approve), or `cancelled` (abandon).
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:56:The human is the only role that can unblock `human-review` gates. This is by design: certain decisions (ship/no-ship, scope changes, external approvals) require human judgment.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:66:This means agents do not need to communicate with each other directly. They communicate through artifacts and the authoritative plan state managed by the orchestrator: one agent writes outputs for its state, `rhei run` advances the task, and the next agent reads the resulting state and artifacts.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:71:draft --> pending --> agent-review --> completed
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:75:            |        agent-review-fix ----+
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:85:The `pending → completed` direct transition allows agents to finish simple tasks that do not require a separate review pass.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:87:The `human-review` state is deliberately isolated: agents can send work into it (from `pending` or `agent-review`), but only a human can transition out of it. This separation ensures that human judgment gates are never bypassed by automated workflows.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:89:Each arrow is a declared transition. Agents follow the `instructions` field on each state to know what work must be completed before the next handoff. The transition itself is then performed either by an interactive/manual worker or by the `rhei run` orchestrator.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:97:| `rhei run`         | Drives the full plan forward under orchestrator authority                       |
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:98:| `rhei next`        | Claims the next ready task for a manual worker (with `--peek` for read-only)    |
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:101:| `rhei reset`       | Returns each task to its resolved profile's `initial` state, removes `runtime/` |
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:103:`rhei run` and the manual-worker flow (`next` / `transition` / `complete`) are mutually exclusive per execution — they never overlap on the same task because `rhei run` holds transition responsibility for the states it drives. The typical manual-worker loop is `next` (claim) → work → `transition` (advance as needed) → `complete` (finish, record result, release).
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:109:The simplest way to use Rhei. No callbacks, no `workflow.sh`, no glue code.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:111:1. Configure your default agent once:
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:115:   echo '{"agent": "claude-code"}' > ~/.config/rhei/settings.json
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:123:   rhei run plan.rhei.md
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:126:Rhei spawns the configured agent for each task, composing a prompt from the state machine instructions and the task content. The agent does the work for the current state, writes any required artifacts, and exits. `rhei run` then performs the state transition. No scaffolding required.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:128:For state-specific agents (e.g., a different agent or model for review):
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:135:    agent: claude-code
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:136:    agent_mode: yolo
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:137:    agent_timeout: 30m
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:138:  agent-review:
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:140:    agent: codex
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:141:    agent_mode: safe
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:142:    agent_timeout: 20m
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:145:Agents are referenced by string id only — `agent:` is resolved against the
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:146:merged `agents` registry (built-ins + `~/.config/rhei/settings.json` +
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:147:`<plan-root>/.rhei/settings.json`). To use a CLI that isn't a built-in, add
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:148:it to the registry instead of inlining it on the state. Run-time overrides
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:149:are available via `--agent <AGENT>`, `--agent-mode <MODE>`, and `--model
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:150:<MODEL>` on `rhei run`.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:152:For parallel execution of independent tasks:
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:155:rhei run plan.rhei.md --parallel 4
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:158:See [Agents Specification](rhei-agents.spec.md) for configuration, resolution order, timeout handling, and log capture.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:162:One agent session acts as both writer and worker. This is useful when the agent session itself drives the workflow rather than `rhei run`.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:170:This is the default for small, well-scoped work within a single agent session. The plan still provides value: it gives the human a structured view of progress, and the agent a memory of what it has and hasn't done. For larger work or multi-agent workflows, Pattern 0 (`rhei run`) is preferred.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:174:For larger work, the plan writer and plan worker run in separate agent sessions — possibly days apart.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:178:3. **Session 2 (execution):** A new agent session invokes the plan worker. It reads the plan fresh, selects the first eligible task, and begins work.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:179:4. **Subsequent sessions:** If the worker stops (human gate, end of session, ambiguity), a new session picks up where it left off by re-reading the plan.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:185:When a plan's DAG has independent branches (tasks with no shared dependencies), multiple workers can operate in parallel.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:203:Here, Task 1 and Task 3 have no dependency relationship. Two workers can implement them concurrently. Task 4 remains blocked until both Task 2 and Task 3 are completed.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:211:# Claim the next ready task (assigns without transitioning, prints instructions)
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:214:# ... agent does the work ...
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:216:# Advance state when ready (e.g., draft → pending, or pending → agent-review)
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:226:rhei transition plan.rhei.md --task 3 --from pending --to agent-review
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:229:The `--from` flag is the key: the command acquires a file lock, verifies the task is still in the expected state, and only then writes the new state. If another worker already claimed the task, the command fails with a conflict error — the losing worker re-reads the plan and picks a different task.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:233:For `rhei run --parallel N`, the same concurrency rule applies, but the spawned agents are not the ones issuing transition commands. Each spawned agent works only on the current state of its assigned task and exits. `rhei run` serializes the resulting state changes, which keeps transition authority centralized even when task work is distributed across multiple agents.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:237:If parallel workers are distributed across multiple branches or machines, the single-file lock approach breaks down (leading to Git merge conflicts). In these highly concurrent scenarios, agents use **Directory Workspaces**.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:244:Plans that require human approval use the `human-review` state as a gate.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:255:- All agents stop work on that task.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:259:Meanwhile, agents continue working on other branches of the DAG that are not blocked by this gate. The plan stays productive even when one branch is waiting on human input.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:263:For exploratory or long-running projects, tasks start as `draft` — placeholder titles that are not yet ready for execution.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:267:3. The agent works in `draft`: it analyzes the current state of the project, determines the most elegant approach, and writes a concrete task description.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:268:4. In interactive/manual execution, the agent transitions `draft` → `pending` via `rhei transition`. Under `rhei run`, the spawned agent exits after writing the concrete task description and any required draft artifacts, and `rhei run` performs the `draft` → `pending` transition.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:269:5. Work then continues in `pending`, either in the same manual session or through the next `rhei run` pass.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:271:This prevents agents from planning against stale or incomplete project state. The `draft` state is a signal: "this task exists in the plan but needs analysis before it can be specified and executed." Because `rhei next` claims without transitioning, the agent has a dedicated phase to do the analysis work before advancing the state.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:275:Beyond agent-driven workflows, Rhei plans can be advanced programmatically through the transition callback system. State machines declare `on_leave` and `on_enter` callbacks that fire during transitions — they can approve, reject, or redirect transitions, turning the plan into an executable workflow engine.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:277:Callbacks are supported for bash (via `--handlers`), TypeScript/JavaScript (NAPI), Python (PyO3), and Java (JNI). See [Transitions Specification](rhei-transitions.spec.md) for the formal `TransitionContext` / `TransitionResult` API and [Transition Callback Examples](rhei-callbacks.spec.md) for per-language code.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:281:When the same task should be run once per model and then synthesized, prefer one shared task state with `all_targets` over cloning one state or one task per model. `rhei run` executes the state once per listed target; artifact paths and prompts template on `{target}`, `{target.slug}`, `{agent}`, `{agent.mode}`, and `{model}`. A downstream `summarize` state then consumes the per-target artifacts and writes one final result.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:283:See [States Specification — `all_targets`](rhei-states.spec.md#per-state-fields) for the schema, selector grammar, and a worked example.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:288:expanded by the orchestrator while `rhei run` is executing. This is useful when
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:289:follow-up work should only exist after a concrete artifact is produced.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:291:One example is a multi-agent review loop:
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:293:1. A seed review task fans out into one agent run per configured model and writes per-model findings files.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:294:2. After each spawned reviewer exits successfully, `rhei run` advances the task according to the declared transitions and records the consolidated result artifact for the review pass.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:296:4. Each verification task is then executed by its assigned agent. The agent records whether the issue is reproducible and relevant, writes its result artifact, and exits.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:297:5. `rhei run` advances each verification task after the subprocess exits.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:307:The orchestrator expands this workspace as review artifacts arrive.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:335:until the review artifact justifies them. The checked-in example lives in
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:340:Program states execute a fixed command instead of spawning an AI agent — use them for deterministic workflow steps (builds, tests, linting, deployment) where an agent would add latency and cost without value. Programs communicate outcomes through exit codes, so transitions from program states can declare an `exit_code` condition that routes automatically. Program and agent states coexist in the same state machine: a common pattern is an agent-program feedback loop where the agent implements code, a deterministic build/test program verifies, and failures return control to the agent.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:342:See [Program States Specification](rhei-programs.spec.md) for program declaration, the full exit-code evaluation algorithm, timeout handling, and validation rules.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:346:A Rhei plan can model a CI/CD pipeline where each task is a pipeline stage. The state machine encodes the pipeline's control flow, and callbacks integrate with build systems, test runners, and deployment tools.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:374:Task 5 starts as `draft` — it will only be promoted to `pending` after staging is verified. The pipeline advances automatically through callbacks, but human gates can be inserted at any stage.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:380:- **Resumability.** A new agent session can pick up any plan mid-execution. No context beyond the file is needed.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:383:- **Composability.** Different agents (writer, worker, reviewer) interact with the same file through well-defined, non-overlapping edits. The state machine prevents conflicts by making illegal transitions impossible.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:390:- [Agents Specification](rhei-agents.spec.md) — agent configuration, invocation, timeout, and log capture
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:392:- [Transitions Specification](rhei-transitions.spec.md) — formal state transition system, callbacks, and YAML schema
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:393:- [Transition Callback Examples](rhei-callbacks.spec.md) — callback implementations across languages
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:397:- [Run Command](rhei-run.spec.md) — `rhei run` behavioral contract
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-usage.spec.md:400:- [Install Skills](rhei-install-skills.spec.md) — `rhei install-skills` command for agent integration
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:1:# `rhei run`
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:3:Drive a plan end-to-end by repeatedly claiming the next ready task, spawning the state's agent or program, waiting for completion, and performing the resulting transition. `rhei run` operates under `orchestrator` authority: the orchestrator — not the spawned subprocess — owns every state transition. See [Agents Specification — Completion Authority](rhei-agents.spec.md#completion-authority) for the full authority contract.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:5:This document specifies the command contract and execution loop. The live terminal UI is specified separately in [rhei-run-tui.spec.md](rhei-run-tui.spec.md).
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:10:rhei run <RHEI_PLAN_OR_WORKSPACE> [flags]
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:21:| `--dry-run`              | false   | Print the sequence of transitions that would be made without executing them |
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:22:| `--no-callbacks`         | false   | Skip execution of `on_leave` / `on_enter` callbacks                        |
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:23:| `--continue-on-error`    | false   | Continue to the next task when an agent or program exits non-zero          |
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:24:| `--parallel <N>`         | 1       | Maximum number of agents or programs to run concurrently (0 = unlimited)   |
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:32:| `--no-agent`            | Disable agent spawning; use callback-only advancement                   |
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:33:| `--agent <AGENT>`       | Override the agent for this run                                         |
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:34:| `--agent-mode <MODE>`   | Override the agent mode (named flag set) for this run                   |
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:35:| `--model <MODEL>`       | Override the model for this run                                         |
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:41:| `--no-program`                 | Disable program spawning; use callback-only advancement for program states       |
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:42:| `--program-timeout <DURATION>` | Override the program timeout for this run (applied per program state)            |
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:46:`rhei run` runs passes until no further forward progress is possible:
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:48:Mode selection: `rhei run` uses orchestrated subprocess execution whenever any reachable non-terminal, non-gating state declares autonomous work via `program`, `agent`, `target`, `all_targets`, `model`, or `all_models`. Callback-only advancement is entered only when no such state exists, or when the caller explicitly disables spawning with `--no-agent` and/or `--no-program`. If a state declares model/target-driven work but no agent transport resolves, `rhei run` fails with a missing-agent configuration error; it does not silently fall back to callback-only transitions for that state.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:51:2. Scan all tasks and compute the *ready set*: tasks whose `**Prior:**` are all in terminal states, whose current state is non-terminal and non-gating, and whose current state's required `inputs:` all exist. Tasks whose current state declares `poll:` and whose `metadata.tasks.<id>.pollNextAttemptAt.<state-name>` is later than the current wall-clock time are excluded from the ready set until the interval elapses. See [Next Command](rhei-next.spec.md#default-behavior-claim-mode) for the full claimability rule and [Polling States](#polling-states) for the poll scheduling rule.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:52:3. Up to `--parallel` tasks from the ready set are executed concurrently, subject to the [concurrent-state rule](#parallel-execution): at most one ready task per non-concurrent state is scheduled per pass. For each task:
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:53:   - Resolve the state's target: either an agent subprocess (`agent` or resolved target selector) or a program (`program`).
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:54:   - Spawn the subprocess with the state's resolved instructions, environment (`RHEI_*` variables defined in [Agents Specification — Environment Variables](rhei-agents.spec.md#environment-variables)), and timeout.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:55:   - Wait for the subprocess to exit or for the timeout to fire. On timeout, send `SIGTERM`, grace 10 s, then `SIGKILL`.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:56:4. On subprocess exit, evaluate the state's [Completion Condition](rhei-agents.spec.md#completion-condition): exit code `0` plus every required `outputs:` artifact present on disk.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:57:5. If the condition holds, select the first declared transition whose `condition` / `exit_code` matches and execute it. The subprocess **must not** call `rhei transition` or `rhei complete`; the orchestrator owns the transition.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:58:6. If the condition fails (non-zero exit or missing outputs), route through the state's error or timeout transition per [Agents Specification — Execution Loop](rhei-agents.spec.md#execution-loop). When no error transition is declared and `--continue-on-error` is unset, `rhei run` aborts with a non-zero exit code.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:61:`rhei run` does not transition out of [gating states](rhei-states.spec.md#per-state-fields) — exiting one requires an explicit human-initiated `rhei transition` call.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:63:Gating states are a barrier, not an immediate global abort. If one task enters a
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:64:gating state while other non-gating tasks are already running, or while other
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:65:independent non-gating tasks remain ready, `rhei run` lets that remaining
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:66:non-gating work finish. The run halts for human input only when the remaining
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:68:gating dependency. In other words: a gate waits for everyone else to complete,
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:73:With `--dry-run`, `rhei run` performs the same scan and selection logic but prints each planned transition instead of executing subprocesses or callbacks. Output format:
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:79:No file lock is acquired, no markdown is rewritten, and no runtime artifacts are created.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:83:With `--parallel N`, up to `N` subprocesses run concurrently. The orchestrator:
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:86:- Writes one line to `runtime/transitions.log` per `SlotAssigned` and one per `SlotReleased`; see [Run TUI Specification — Transition Journal](rhei-run-tui.spec.md#transition-journal).
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:87:- Serializes every state write through its own file lock, so two agents completing at once cannot corrupt the plan.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:89:Tasks whose transitions would race on the same task node are never scheduled in parallel: scheduling is driven by the ready set, which excludes tasks already in flight.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:93:States that declare a [`poll:`](rhei-states.spec.md#polling-states) block are time-triggered: each attempt spawns one subprocess, the engine evaluates transitions, and a self-loop transition means "retry after `poll.interval`". Between attempts, the orchestrator:
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:96:- Releases the `--parallel` slot so other ready tasks may run.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:99:If, at the end of a pass, every remaining non-terminal task is either in a gating state, blocked behind a gating dependency, or blocked by a pending `pollNextAttemptAt`, `rhei run` sleeps until the earliest `pollNextAttemptAt` across all blocked poll tasks (bounded below by 1 s to avoid busy-looping) and then begins a new pass. If no poll deadline is pending and only gating remains, the run exits as it does today.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:101:Once `stateVisits.<state-name>` reaches `poll.max_attempts`, the engine refuses to select a self-loop transition and picks the first matching non-self-loop instead. If no non-self-loop transition matches, the run halts that task with a "polling exhausted with no matching non-self-loop transition" error — `--continue-on-error` applies as with any other task failure. A non-self-loop exit at any attempt clears both `pollNextAttemptAt.<state-name>` and `stateVisits.<state-name>`.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:105:The [`concurrent`](rhei-states.spec.md#per-state-fields) flag on a `StateDef` determines whether multiple ready tasks in the same state may be scheduled together in one pass:
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:107:- `concurrent: true` — any number of ready tasks in this state may be scheduled together (bounded by `--parallel`).
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:108:- `concurrent: false` (the default) — at most one ready task in this state is scheduled per pass. Additional tasks remain ready and are picked up on the next pass.
/home/vjovanov/c/rhei/docs/specs/rhei-run.spec.md:114:`rhei run` drives the full plan forward under orchestrator authority. It is mutually exclusive per execution with the manual-worker flow (`next` / `transition` / `complete`) — they never overlap on the same task because `rhei run` holds transition responsibility for the states it drives.
