   136	
   137	### `exit_code` Field
   138	
   139	Added to the transition definition schema (see [Transitions Specification](rhei-transitions.spec.md)):
   140	
   141	| Field | Type | Required | Description |
   142	|-------|------|----------|-------------|
   143	| `exit_code` | integer, integer array, or `"nonzero"` | No | Exit-code condition for automatic transitions from program states. |
   144	
   145	Values:
   146	- **integer** (`0`, `1`, `42`): matches that exact exit code.
   147	- **integer array** (`[1, 2, 3]`): matches any listed exit code.
   148	- **`"nonzero"`**: matches any non-zero exit code not already matched by a more specific transition from the same source state.
   149	
   150	### Evaluation Order
   151	
   152	When a program exits and has not already advanced the task (via `rhei transition` or `rhei complete`):
   153	
   154	1. Collect all transitions from the current state that declare an `exit_code` field.
   155	2. Evaluate specific matches first: integer and integer-array conditions are checked against the actual exit code.
   156	3. If no specific match and the exit code is non-zero, evaluate `"nonzero"` transitions.
   157	4. If exactly one transition matches, fire it (with its `on_leave`/`on_enter` callbacks).
   158	5. If multiple transitions match at the same specificity level, also evaluate `condition` fields to disambiguate. If still ambiguous after conditions, it is a validation error.
   159	6. If no transition matches and exit code is `0`, log a warning: `warning: program exited 0 but task {id} did not advance from '{state}'`.
   160	7. If no transition matches and exit code is non-zero, log an error and apply the `--continue-on-error` policy.
   161	
   162	### Mixing Exit-Code and Manual Transitions
   163	
   164	Programs may also call `rhei transition` or `rhei complete` directly via subprocess invocation, just like agents. When a program does so, the task state changes before the program exits, and exit-code evaluation is skipped entirely — the explicit transition takes precedence.
   165	
   166	If a transition from a program state has no `exit_code` field, it is available for manual invocation (`rhei transition`) or for the program to call directly, but it will never be selected by exit-code evaluation.
   167	
   168	This allows hybrid approaches where a program handles the common case via exit codes and calls `rhei transition` for edge cases that need more nuanced routing.
   169	
   170	## Timeout Handling
   171	
   172	Program timeout uses the same mechanism as agent timeout.
   173	
   174	### Configuration
   175	
   176	Timeout can be set at three levels:
   177	
   178	1. **Per-state** — `program_timeout` field on the state definition:
   179	   ```yaml
   180	   states:
   181	     build:
   182	       program: "make build"
   183	       program_timeout: 10m
   184	   ```
   185	
   186	2. **Global default** — `program_timeout` in settings:
   187	   ```json
   188	   { "program_timeout": "15m" }
   189	   ```
   190	
   191	3. **CLI override** — `--program-timeout` flag on `rhei run` overrides all levels.
   192	
   193	Resolution: CLI override > state-level > settings-level.
   194	
   195	Duration format is the same as `agent_timeout`: `30s`, `5m`, `1h`, `2h30m`. See [Agents Specification — Duration Format](rhei-agents.spec.md#duration-format).
   196	
   197	### Behavior
   198	
   199	Program timeout uses the same SIGTERM → 10 s grace → SIGKILL sequence and the same timeout-transition evaluation as agent timeout. See [Agents Specification — Timeout Behavior](rhei-agents.spec.md#timeout-behavior) for the full step-by-step. The only program-specific differences are:
   200	
   201	- The log line reads `program timed out after {duration}` (not `agent timed out`).
   202	- The state-level field is `program_timeout` (not `agent_timeout`).
   203	
   204	Timeout transitions fire with `triggeredBy: 'system'`. See [Transitions Specification — Agent Timeout Trigger](rhei-transitions.spec.md#6-agent-timeout-trigger-triggeredby-system) for the transition selection rules.
   205	
   206	## Log Capture
   207	
   208	Program stdout and stderr are captured using the same log format and naming conventions as agents. All output is written to `runtime/logs/` relative to the workspace or plan root.
